title: booth_babe
body:
A [b]trade show model[/b] (also known as a convention [[model]], trade show [[hostess]], booth companion, or booth professional; a term that has been used only in Japan is companion lady but today more often used is event companion (イベントコンパニオン)) is an assistant that works with a company's sales representatives at a trade show exhibit, working on the floor space or a [[booth seating]], and representing a company to attendees. Such models are used to draw in attendees and can provide them with basic information about product or services, and may be used to distribute marketing materials or gather customer information for future promotions. Attire varies and depends on the nature of the show and on the image the company would like to portray, and they sometimes wear wardrobe that is particular to the company, product, or service represented.

Trade show models are typically not regular employees of the company, but are hired as they make a company's booth more visibly distinguishable from other booths with which it competes for attendee attention. If needed, they can explain or disseminate information on the company and its product and service, and can assist a company in handling a large number of attendees which the company might otherwise not have enough employees to accommodate, therefore increasing the number of sales or leads resulting from participation in the show. The models can be skilled at drawing attendees into the booth, engaging them in conversation, and at spurring interest in the product, service, or company.

title: la_serena_de_la_noche_(merryweather)
body:
[[Original]] character by [[Merryweather]], [[AT2.]] and "ironmouse":[https://twitter.com/ironmouse]. La Serena de la Noche is an anthropomorphic (and genderbent) representation of [i]El sereno de la noche[/i] (lit. "night dew"), the [b]humid outdoor air at night[/b], which in Latin-American folklore is believed to contain "bad air" or "evil spirits" that can cause sickness. This makes Serena a humanoid miasma spirit of the night.

Serena appears as a massively [[tall_female|tall]] [[dark-skinned_female|Hispanic woman]] with [[long hair|long]] [[brown hair|dark brown]] hair and [[aqua eyes|turquoise eyes]]. She has turquoise teardrop-shaped [[earrings]]. She wears a low-cut [[lace-trimmed dress|lace-trimmed]] [[black dress]] (inside colored turquoise) with [[elbow gloves|elbow-length]] [[black gloves]] and [[high heels]]. She also wears a black [[veil]] and a wide-brimmed [[black headwear|black]] [[hat]] (again, inside colored turqoise). Overall she resembles [[Hasshaku-sama]] but with a darker color scheme.

Serena also carries a normal-sized (appearing small in her hands) [[spear]] with a lantern hanging off near the spear tip. This is a reference to historical [i]sereno[/i] nightwatchmen, who were known to also carry a similar style of spear and lantern in Latin America.

h5. Concept art

* post #4759041 [tn]with veil[/tn]
* post #4759044 [tn]without[/tn]

h4. See also

h4. External links

title: ankle_lock
body:
A wrestling move where the wrestler applies pressure to the opponent's ankle and lifts it from the ground. With one hand the wrestler will grab either the toes or the outside of the foot, then with the other wrap the ankle to create a "hole" for the joint. 

A grapevine variation sees the wrestler applying the ankle lock hold and then falling to the mat and scissoring the leg of the opponent. This stops the opponent from rolling out of the move and makes it harder for him/her to crawl to the ropes but lessens the pressure that can be applied. The move can be executed from a kneeling position or a standing position.

Popular users of this move are Ken Shamrock, Kurt Angle, Jake Hager and Shelton Benjamin.

title: fujiwara_takumi
body:
The protagonist of [[Initial D]]. Often seen driving his iconic two-tone panda [[Toyota Sprinter Trueno]].

Takumi is somewhat pokey and can come off as awkward or dense, but is a natural behind the wheel and possesses an almost symbiotic relationship with his car - a result of being made to drive it from a very early age, day in and out, be it clear, rainy or snowy, up and down the mountain road next to his town to deliver tofu to the mountaintop hotel for his father, [[Fujiwara Bunta]].

title: inui_shinji
body:
The final opponent of [[Fujiwara Takumi]] in [[Initial D]]. 

Shinji is essentially a mirror-match of Takumi's initial appearance: a young boy (either 15 or 16), in an underpowered [[Toyota Sprinter Trueno]], who has been driving from a very early age (in this case, to relieve his overworked mother) and has an almost-unnatural feel for his home course, the Tsubaki Line, enabling him to drive extremely fast for somewhat childish reasons (Takumi's high speed runs came as a result of him wanting to be done with tofu deliveries faster, whereas Shinji has an odd fixation with braking as little as possible and has experience on both sides of the road due to going to school on the passenger side while his mother drove him there and returning home behind the wheel).

Due to his very young age, Shinji is prone to somewhat childish outbursts (such as being too nervous to show up on time for his race against Takumi, or intentionally allowing a rival to pass so he could show off an overtake) and sometimes daydreams of "wings" on Takumi's car.

title: matou_byakuya
body:
Minor character from [[Fate/Zero|Fate/Zero]]. Byakuya is [[Matou Shinji|Shinji]]'s father, both considered failures by the family head, [[Matou Zouken|Zouken Matou]]. 

He has [[short hair|short]] [[blue hair|blue]] [[wavy hair]] and [[blue eyes]]. He wears a disheveled black [[suit]].

In [[Fate/Zero|Fate/Zero]], he was passed over as heir to the family due to holding almost no magical potential and thus resents his more capable brother [[Matou Kariya|Kariya]]. A bitter alcoholic, he apathetically helped Zouken do his bidding, by acclimating [[Matou Sakura|Sakura]] to the worms and training her to be worthy of becoming the next head of the Matou house. Despite this, he's very determined to keep his son away from the truths of the Matou family, so he sends him to study abroad when the 4th Grail War starts.

Byakuya died 3 years prior to the events of [[Fate/Stay Night]]. He kept hiding more things from Shinji, such as the truth of Sakura's adoption. After he accidentally finds the worms basement and the truth about the Matou family, Byakuya cuts all ties with his son and dies shortly after.

title: don't_look_down_on_central_(meme)
body:
Line uttered by [[Symboli Rudolf (Umamusume)|]] in Chapter 18 of [[Umamusume: Cinderella Gray]].

The original scene features Rudolf saying the above line while making an intimidating expression with [[shaded eyes]] and one hand propped under her right cheek ("ref.":[https://livedoor.blogimg.jp/izumich-wjzrnqvn/imgs/9/e/9ec97b7c.jpg], top left panel).

The above line and scene are frequently memed among the Japanese and Chinese [[Umamusume]] fanbase. Often, the last word will be swapped out, forming a "Don't look down on X" snowclone.

h5. Original line and translations

* 中央を無礼るなよ [tn]Original Japanese[/tn]
* 不要在中央面前无礼/不要在中央面前無禮 [tn]Memetic Chinese translation (simp. and trad.)[/tn] 
* Don't make light of Central [tn]English, fits the original context better.[/tn]
* Don't look down on Central [tn]English, fits most memed examples better.[/tn] 

h4. See also

* [[Umamusume: Cinderella Gray]]
* [[Symboli Rudolf (Umamusume)|]]

title: cart
body:
For tagging purposes a cart is an animal or human driven two or more wheeled vehicle used for carrying loads that is pulled or pushed. They're similar to carriages, but  the carriage tag covers vehicles specifically design for passenger transport, while the cart tag is intended for vehicles designed to transport cargo.

A true cart is an open two-wheeled vehicle for carrying loads that is pulled by animals or humans, for tagging purposes these will be tagged as a "pullcart".

The term "cart" over time has evolved to also refer to a variety of small wheeled vehicles that are pushed or pulled and include vehicles that have more than two wheels.

For the small motor vehicle, see [[go-kart]].

title: chiyo_(genshin_impact)
body:
Mikoshi Chiyo (Japanese: 御輿千代 Mikoshi Chiyo), also known as Torachiyo (Japanese: 虎千代), was an oni and a member of the Mikoshi Clan who lived around five hundred years ago. She was the biological mother of Iwakura Doukei and the adoptive mother of Mikoshi Nagamasa.

Chiyo was once a valuable ally of the Raiden Shogun Baal's and campaigned with her against the dark forces that emerged during the cataclysm. However, she was swallowed whole by a "beast of sin" and while inside its stomach, was tainted by the darkness. Even though she managed to rip the beast apart and slay it, she was forever changed: she would later turn her blade on Baal, after which she was defeated and badly injured. Her ultimate fate is unknown.

title: mailbox_(incoming_mail)
body:
A physical receptacle into which postal carriers deliver incoming mail, to be picked up by the recipient. Also known as a letterbox*, letter plate, letter hole, mail slot, etc. ("Wikipedia":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Letter_box]).  Some mailboxes feature an arm that can be flipped up to indicate that there is some outgoing mail within for the postal carrier to retrieve when they come by delivering mail.

Examples: post #951740, post #913214


For tagging purposes, distinct from [[postbox (outgoing mail)]], which is for outgoing mail.


*However, [[letterboxed|letterbox]] is used here to refer to the image composition technique.

body:
Fully-sentient Gear from [[Guilty Gear]]. She was tired of humans pushing around Gears and turned them against them, starting the 100-year war known as the Crusades. The war ended with the victory of the humans when the Sacred Order of Holy Knights, a human resistance, sealed Justice away causing all Gears to cease to function.

Eventually, Justice was revived by [[Testament (Guilty Gear)|]] only to be defeated and destroyed by the winner of the tournament in Guilty Gear, which, officially, was [[Sol Badguy]]. Since her death in Guilty Gear, she appears in its sequels as a secret unlockable character (in Guilty Gear XX Accent Core, she, along with Kliff, are absent, but in Guilty Gear XX Accent Core Plus, she is unlocked from the beginning). She is also [[Dizzy (Guilty Gear)|]]'s mother.

title: dizzy_(guilty_gear)
body:
Dizzy is a character from the [[Guilty Gear]] series and the final boss of the second game in the series, [i]Guilty Gear X[/i].

She is the daughter of [[Justice (guilty gear)|]] and an unknown human. She is not fully able to control her Gear powers, and her [[wings]] can transform (into [[Undine (guilty gear)|]] and [[Necro_(guilty_gear)|]]) and fight for her, against her will if necessary. After being hunted relentlessly by the Post-War Administration Bureau, which fears her power, she has found a haven on the Mayship, with the Jellyfish Pirates.

By [[Guilty Gear 2]], she is married to [[Ky Kiske]] and has given birth to a son, [[Sin Kiske]]. During the events of [[Guilty Gear Xrd]]'s Revelator story line, it is revealed that [spoiler][[Sol Badguy]] and [[Jack-O' Valentine]] are her parents.[/spoiler]

title: cinnabar_(houseki_no_kuni)
body:
A character from [[Houseki no Kuni]], a personification of the red, [[mercury (element)|]]-containing mineral cinnabar.

Small "clouds" of native mercury appear to float around Cinnabar at all times. In the same way that mercury is harmful to human beings (due to its toxicity) and destructive to metals such as aluminum (due to forming amalgams that compromise their strength), Cinnabar's very presence is hazardous to their fellow Gems. As a result, they have been forced to live a mostly solitary existence, well removed from the "school" where the rest of the Gems live.

Known as "Shinsha" in Japanese. [[Kongou Sensei]] and Shinsha are the only Gems who use Japanese names instead of English in the original Japanese version.

title: sendai_hakurei_no_miko
body:
先代博麗の巫女 ([i]Sendai Hakurei no Miko[/i], "The previous generation's Hakurei shrine maiden")

A fanmade [[M.U.G.E.N]] character by MUGEN author Pre-to and [[Touhou]] [[Original]] Character.

Depicted as [[hakurei_reimu|Reimu]]'s predecessor. She was apparently not created with a proper given(first) name, so her name may vary. Usually portrayed as a powerful physical fighter.

She wears a [[nontraditional miko|customized]] miko uniform consisting of a one-piece skintight [[leotard]] rather than a sarashi (frequently resulting in [[sideboob]]), sturdy [[combat boots]], and sometimes [[hakama pants]] rather than a skirt.

Also, unlike Reimu, she does not wear a ribbon on the back of her head, although in some depictions, she wears one to tie her long hair together near the end. Some artists depict her as muscular and/or covered in scars.

She is usually depicted as Reimu's mother, though as a fan character her relation to Reimu on the Hakurei family tree can change with each depiction.

A very popular fanwork featuring this character is [[Osana Reimu]] and its sequel [[Reireimu]], a story about Sendai Miko, a young Reimu, and an [[EX-Rumia|adult]] [[Rumia]]. This version looks almost identical to Reimu herself, only taller and more endowed, and oftentimes wearing a mask of some sort.

title: yamato-no-kami_yasusada
body:
A [[Touken Ranbu]] character. Official art by [[kumita_(sumica)|Kumita]]. Voiced by [[Ichiki Mitsuhiro]].

Both he and [[Kashuu Kiyomitsu]] are personifications of swords owned by [[Okita Souji]]. Unlike Kiyomitsu, who resents Okita for abandoning him, Yasusada is very fond of Okita and hasn't gotten over his former master's death, to the point of dressing and occasionally acting like him. 

He has [[black hair]] worn in a [[high ponytail]], [[blue eyes]], and a [[mole under eye|mole under his left eye]]. His standard outfit is a [[white scarf]], a [[Shinsengumi]] [[haori]], [[black gloves|black]] "[[bridal gauntlets|bridal gauntlet]]"-type gloves, a dark blue [[hakama]], black [[tabi]] and [[zouri]] with blue straps.

Normally, he has a carefree personality with his comrades, but is ruthless and sadistic in battles. title: gyeongsang_korean_text
body:
Korean dialect spoken in the Gyeongsang region.

This dialect is characterized by merging of [i]ae[/i] and [i]e[/i], as well as [i]eu[/i] and [i]eo[/i], plus dropping of [i]w[/i] and [i]y[/i] (/j/) after consonants. Southern Gyeongsang also lacks the "tense" fortis consonant [i]ss[/i] of Standard Korean; speakers will instead substitute it with a "lax" [i]s[/i].

Southern Gyeongsang (especially the Busan variant) is frequently used in translations and fanworks to adapt Japanese [[Kansaiben]] (analogous to use of Southern American English in English translations and fanworks). Japanese characters who speak Kansai dialect are frequently depicted speaking Busan dialect in Korean translations and fancomics.

She is very straight-forward and blunt whenever she has something to say and occasionally every now and then in her dialogue lets out ribbits ([i]kero[/i] in Japanese). She is very adamant about being called by her first name, Tsuyu, and immediately corrects anybody who calls her by her last name, Asui. A majority of the time she has a "[[:>]]" expression on her face no matter what mood she is in, only going away when she opens her mouth.

She is the older sister of [[Asui Samidare]] and [[Asui Satsuki|Satsuki]].

title: scarlet_devil_mansion
body:
The setting of stages 4-6 and the extra stage of the [[Touhou]] game [[Embodiment of Scarlet Devil]].

The Scarlet Devil Mansion is described as a western-style mansion situated near [[Gensokyo]]'s [[Misty Lake]]. Official depictions are inconsistent on whether the mansion sits on the lake's far side, or on an island in the middle of the lake.

The home of [[Remilia Scarlet]], her [[sisters|sister]] [[Flandre Scarlet|Flandre]], friend [[Patchouli Knowledge]] and her little devil, [[Koakuma]], maid [[Izayoi Sakuya]] and the [[fairy maid (touhou)|]]s, and gatekeeper [[Hong Meiling]]. [[Rumia]], the fairy duo [[Cirno]] and [[Daiyousei]], and the mermaid [[Wakasagihime]], who all live at or near Misty Lake, are also frequently seen in the area.

Known for its immense library, the [[Voile]].

h4. See also

* [[Gensokyo]]

title: voile
body:
The fanon name for the [[Scarlet Devil Mansion]]'s [[library]] in [[Touhou]].

The stage 4 theme music of [[Embodiment of Scarlet Devil]] is named ヴワル魔法図書館 ([i]Vuwaru Mahou Toshokan[/i], lit. "Voile, the Magic Library"). Based on this, some of the English-speaking fandom originally believed Voile to be the name of the [[Scarlet Devil Mansion]]'s library. However, this is not canon and [[ZUN]] has consistently referred to this library as "Scarlet Devil Mansion's Library" or "The Magic Library" in official works without any mention of "Voile". See also topic #9233.

The library is tended to by [[Patchouli Knowledge]], a large squad of [[fairy maid (touhou)|fairy maids]], and, allegedly, [[Koakuma]]. [[Kirisame Marisa]] frequently breaks in to "borrow" (read: steal) books, but occasionally will sit peacefully with Patchouli.

The library is often depicted as a massive tesseract (larger on the inside) or even a pocket dimension attached to the mansion.

h4. See also

* [[Gensokyo]]

A vast, deep lake near the [[Forest of Magic]] in [[Touhou]]. The [[Scarlet Devil Mansion]] sits either on the far side, or on an island in the middle of the lake - canon is inconsistent on which. Fairies [[Cirno]] and [[Daiyousei]] live on the lake's edge, and mermaid [[Wakasagihime]] lives in the lake itself. It's believed [[Rumia]] also lives somewhere in the area.

title: setsubun
body:
[b]Setsubun[/b] (節分, lit. "seasonal division") is the last day of winter in the Japanese calendar. It usually corresponds to February 3rd in the Gregorian calendar.

A ritual performed on this day is to throw roasted soybeans in order to drive away [[oni]]; this is known as [[mamemaki]].

In the Kansai region, it's customary to eat [[makizushi]] while facing this year's lucky direction; this practice is known as [[ehoumaki]].

title: capotain
body:
A type of tall, narrow-brimmed hat with a flat top and slight conical profile. Historically heavily associated with the Puritan movement in England. Sometimes also called a "pilgrim hat" or a "sugarloaf hat", though these two names can also refer to other styles of hat.

In fiction this style of hat is frequently given to characters who work as witch hunters or inquisitors. In such cases the hat will usually be festooned with one or multiple [[leather belt]]s wrapped around the brim and/or crown.

Because of the above depiction of the capotain in fiction, this hat is also called a "witch hunter('s) hat".
